{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4a5116f3-2189-4eb7-b8f8-c98eef68cca5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "05e21a986c13a31d09e7d677017441175c89ead4c1345af265c57d30313cecdc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "sjo-15", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-02-23", "title": null, "content": "I saw some snooty reviews claiming this movie has nothing to say or offer apart from being funny and some comedy horror gore. Isn't that enough? Not every movie has to educate or comment on something heavy. Being entertaining is enough. And this movie is entertaining.\n\nIts funny. Its a bit gory. The performances are engaging. It does what one would expect, given the trailer and film outline.\n\nNeeson is brilliant as is everyone else. Its fun."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2753ec97-8611-4b2d-b2fd-f0cdbc035490", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "84e19b5fc08e6b7bbdd20fb6cd55c0a65fa83f17381df7a175c0cad3ba0860f2"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "Shawn_13", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "Wasn't expecting too much going into this but having seen it at the cinema, it was actually really good, not the sort of film where there is an emotional story at it's core just none serious comedy/horror.\n\nReally enjoyed it, thought it was funny and entertaining, good bit of dark humor.\n\nLoved the dynamic between the 2 lead characters, suppose the odd serious scene regarding their budding relationship and some really good supporting characters, great acting all round and some outrageous/absurd scenes, overall really good and very rewatchable."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a3f34b69-7bcd-4627-a6ab-4073dc5a79ca", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7551cd0fa6282301fea276fe68de72cbaf8f77f30f57d597dc5e891b52c7d54d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "Beachbum2018", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-08", "title": null, "content": "A few big name actors having a bit of fun with a cliched old horror plot.... that's it!\n\nHave only ever seen 1 movie classed as sci-fi, comedy that got away with it and that was The Martian. This isn't The Martian, or even close to it unfortunately.\n\nNot a lot to say beyond that, other than to add it just doesn't work at all!\n\nBoring, annoying, irritating, and the worst of all it's not even funny! The opening sequence trying to masquerade as Western Australia, clearly isn't Australia for anyone who knows, probably Mexico, or southern US somewhere."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bd427c72-8c28-4689-97e4-e31faabb1b8a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ca675dae660736f574501e0f4dfd4a75466f218baa9e47a83638b0b092af1c4c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "Avoram", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-03-04", "title": null, "content": "Liam Neeson is in it and of course he delivers a reversed \"I will find you and I will kill you\" moment. The film doesn't explain anything, it shows. You see the chain reactions of the spreading spores, every cause and every effect. Nothing is left unclear, and yet it remains tense throughout. There's a single, well placed jump scare, the pacing works, and Rob Collins delivers a surprisingly strong performance after Stranger Things. The mix of humor, suspense, shock moments, and disgust works remarkably well. There's a hint of The Last of Us in the air, but without ever feeling like a copy.\n\nVisual storytelling and standout camera sequences Cold Storage shines with dynamic camera work that treats the fungus, the real threat, almost like a character. One standout sequence follows a cockroach carrying the fungus through a maze of pipes to the surface. It's technically impressive and narratively precise: it shows how the spores spread without a single line of exposition. The audience understands the danger long before the characters do.\n\nThis visual clarity runs through the entire film. The camera stays close to processes, infection pathways, and small details that later have major consequences. It creates a feeling of both control and chaos.\n\nWhy the film works better as its own franchise If Cold Storage were set in The Last of Us universe, fan expectations would be so high that the film would collapse under them. Tone, lore, Cordyceps logic, emotional depth, everything would have to be perfect. Any deviation would be criticized instantly.\n\nBecause Cold Storage is starting its own franchise, it can be bold, weird, and surprising. It can mix humor with horror, embrace absurd moments, and establish its own rules without purists complaining.\n\nAnd honestly: Liam Neeson firing an SMG while lying on the floor with a slipped disc would probably be sacrilege in the TLOU canon. Here, it's simply fantastic.\n\nThe novel and the franchise potential The film is based on the 2019 novel by David Koepp, who also wrote the screenplay. The story of a mutating, parasitic fungus from space, Cordyceps novus, offers huge biological and narrative potential for future outbreaks, mutations, or new settings. An extraterrestrial parasite that takes over bodies and evolves intelligently is flexible enough to support multiple films.\n\nThe foundations for a franchise are all there: * a clear, expandable threat * an author who understands his own universe * a tone that blends horror, humor, and science * visual ideas that can grow with each installment What it needs now is simply more viewers to let this universe expand.\n\nWhat makes the film stand out Cold Storage doesn't reinvent the genre, but everything it does, it does well.\n\n* a malfunctioning timer * a dead cat impaled on an antenna, spreading spores * an antagonist who claims he is controlled by others and actually is * environmental storytelling that acts like a silent warning system Instead of characters shouting \"Don't go in there!\", the environment itself takes over that role. A biohazard suit placed a little too conveniently, a broken sensor in a lab, hints of a secret military base, all of it screams \"Something is wrong here\" long before the characters notice. The film uses its world as a subtle but powerful narrative voice.\n\nEverything fits together and explains itself.\n\nConclusion A film for fans of fungal zombie stories, with a touch of humor and a clear visual storytelling style that shows rather than tells. Cold Storage is obvious, fun, disgusting, tense and absolutely worth seeing on the big screen.\n\nPopcorn out, cola up, off to the cinema."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "40f58e16-7cbf-44d4-89f8-984b3b811fb6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f82b86d2836721bf0221e4fff403f3916498763556f914b9059f014e1fcf0d11"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "That_one_kdrama_fanboy", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-03-08", "title": null, "content": "I went into Cold Storage (2026) expecting a fun sci-fi horror ride, and honestly, it delivered exactly that for me. The concept alone hooked me instantly. A deadly parasitic fungus escaping from a sealed military facility and turning a simple night shift into a fight for survival is the kind of chaotic premise I absolutely enjoy. The movie moves fast, keeps the tension alive, and blends horror, sci-fi, and humor in a way that made the experience feel energetic and unpredictable from beginning to end.\n\nJoe Keery was fantastic and brought a lot of charm and personality to the film. His performance felt natural and fun to watch, especially during the intense moments when everything starts spiraling out of control. Georgina Campbell was equally great and balanced the chaos with strong emotional presence. And of course Liam Neeson adds that legendary presence that instantly raises the stakes whenever he appears. The supporting cast including Sosie Bacon, Lesley Manville, and Vanessa Redgrave helped make the world feel even more alive.\n\nWhat I really enjoyed is how the film doesn't take itself too seriously. It knows exactly what kind of movie it wants to be and fully commits to the wild ride. The mix of suspense, humor, and creature-feature chaos kept me entertained throughout. There were moments that were intense, moments that made me laugh, and moments where the sheer absurdity of the situation made the experience even more fun.\n\nEveryone will have their own opinion about this kind of movie, and I respect that. Not every film is meant to resonate the same way with everyone. But for me, I had a great time watching it. I also respect the effort that goes into\n\nmaking a film like this. Behind every scene are people spending countless hours bringing a story to life. And when you feel that passion and energy on screen, it makes the whole experience even more enjoyable."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c5af0649-571d-47b9-8600-4b387e0a162d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:18.802263", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1ca25dec05177a5fdebc00db63a99ebbdbb78ecd38b9fa0434ee2cc43eb2a42b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt8879928", "author": "SyedM-269", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-16", "title": null, "content": "I went into Cold Storage expecting a decent sci-fi thriller, but what I experienced was something far greater - a tense, intelligent, and wildly entertaining film that deserves to be called an instant classic. This movie doesn't just tell a story; it pulls you into a high-stakes nightmare that feels disturbingly real.\n\nFrom the opening moments, the film establishes an atmosphere of unease that never fades. The premise - a scientific threat spiraling beyond control - is handled with chilling realism. Instead of relying on cheap jump scares, the movie builds slow, suffocating tension. Every corridor, every shadow, every sound feels like a warning. You're not just watching events unfold; you're bracing yourself for what might happen next.\n\nWhat truly elevates Cold Storage is its pacing. There is no wasted time. Each scene pushes the narrative forward while deepening the suspense. Just when you think the characters have found safety, the film pulls the rug out from under them, keeping viewers locked in a constant state of anticipation.\n\nThe characters are another major strength. They feel human - flawed, frightened, and determined. Their reactions to the escalating crisis make the danger feel personal. You don't just observe their struggle; you feel it. This emotional connection transforms the film from a simple thriller into a gripping survival story.\n\nVisually, the film excels at creating a claustrophobic environment. The confined spaces and stark lighting amplify the sense of danger, making every moment feel urgent. Combined with excellent sound design, the movie crafts an immersive experience that keeps your heart pounding.\n\nOne of the most surprising elements is the film's use of dark humor. These brief moments of levity don't break the tension - they enhance it. They give the audience a chance to breathe before plunging them back into the chaos, making the suspense even more effective.\n\nBy the time the credits roll, you're left with that rare feeling: complete satisfaction mixed with lingering unease. Cold Storage is the kind of movie that stays with you, replaying in your mind long after it ends. It's thrilling, smart, and relentlessly engaging - the kind of film that reminds you why you love cinema.\n\nIf you enjoy sci-fi thrillers that respect your intelligence, build genuine tension, and deliver a truly immersive experience, this is a must-watch. I can confidently say this is one of the most gripping films I've seen - a true 10/10."}}
